.TH ws_expirer 8 "April 2026" "SYSTEM ADMINISTRATION COMMANDS"

.SH NAME
ws_expirer \- expire and delete workspaces, intended to be run from a cronjob

.SH SYNOPSIS
.B ws_expirer
[\-h] [\-V] [\-F FILESYSTEMS] [\-s SINGLE_SPACE] [\-c] [\-\-configfile CONFIGFILE]

.SH DESCRIPTION
.B ws_expirer
is a system administration tool designed to be run from a cronjob. It handles
the expiration and deletion of workspaces based on their database entries and
performs cleanup of stray directories on the filesystems.

By default, the tool runs in
.B dry-run mode
and only shows what actions would be performed without actually executing them.
Pass
.B \-c
to enable actual cleaning operations.

.B It is strongly recommended to test a configuration in dry-run mode first
and study the output of a manual run before setting up a cronjob.

.B Warning:
anything inside a configured workspace spaces directory can be deleted by
.B ws_expirer
if it matches the workspace naming pattern.

The tool operates in two phases:
.TP 1i
1. Stray directory cleanup
Scans workspace spaces for directories without valid DB entries. Directories
containing a dash (\fIusername\-workspacename\fR pattern) are moved to the
deleted directory. Directories not matching the expected pattern are logged
and require manual intervention.
.TP 1i
2. Database-based expiration
Processes all DB entries: active workspaces past their expiration time are
moved to the deleted directory; workspaces in the deleted directory that
have exceeded their
.B keeptime
(expired) or
.B releasekeeptime
(released by user) are permanently deleted.

.PP

.SH OPTIONS
.TP
\-h, \-\-help
display usage help text
.TP
\-V, \-\-version
show version information
.TP
\-F, \-\-filesystems FILESYSTEMS
comma-separated list of filesystems to process. If not specified, all
configured filesystems are processed.
.TP
\-s, \-\-space SINGLE_SPACE
process only the specified workspace space (path of a single space directory).
.TP
\-c, \-\-cleaner
enable cleaner mode: actually perform deletions instead of dry-run.
.TP
\-\-configfile CONFIGFILE
path to config file (default: \fI/etc/ws.d\fR, \fI/etc/ws.conf\fR).

.SH OPERATION MODES
.SS Dry-Run Mode (default)
When run without the
.B \-c
option,
.B ws_expirer
only simulates the cleanup operations and logs what would be done. This is the
recommended mode for testing a new configuration before enabling actual cleanup.

.SS Cleaner Mode
When
.B \-c
is specified, the tool performs actual file operations:
.RS
.IP \(bu 4
Move expired workspaces to the deleted directory
.IP \(bu 4
Permanently delete workspaces in the deleted directory that have exceeded
.B keeptime
(expired) or
.B releasekeeptime
(user-released)
.IP \(bu 4
Move stray directories (no DB entry) to the deleted directory
.IP \(bu 4
Remove stray deleted directories (in deleted area, no DB entry)
.RE

.SH EMAIL NOTIFICATIONS
The tool sends email notifications using the configured SMTP server:
.TP
Reminder emails
Sent to users when their workspace is within the configured reminder period
before expiration. Requires a mail address stored in the workspace DB entry.
.TP
Error emails
Sent to administrators (configured via
.B adminmail
) when DB errors or other critical conditions are encountered.

Email sending requires
.B smtphost
and
.B mail_from
to be configured.

.SH LOGGING
The tool logs to the console with colors. If
.B expirerlogpath
is set in the configuration file, log output is also written to daily-rotated
log files with timestamps.

.SH RETENTION TIMES
Expired and released workspaces are not deleted immediately but kept in a
recovery area for a configurable time:
.TP
.B keeptime
Number of days to keep an expired workspace before final deletion.
Defaults to 10 days if not set.
.TP
.B releasekeeptime
Number of days to keep a user-released workspace before final deletion.
Defaults to the value of
.B keeptime
if not set.

.SH SETUP
Create a daily cronjob to run
.B ws_expirer
at a regular interval:
.PP
.RS
10 1 * * * /usr/sbin/ws_expirer \-c
.RE
.PP
Note the required
.B \-c
option. Without it,
.B ws_expirer
runs in dry-run mode and performs no file operations.

.SH EXAMPLES
.TP
run in dry-run mode for all filesystems (testing):
.B ws_expirer
.TP
run cleaner mode for all filesystems:
.B ws_expirer \-c
.TP
run cleaner mode for specific filesystems:
.B ws_expirer \-c \-F ws1,ws2,ws3
.TP
run cleaner mode for a single space:
.B ws_expirer \-c \-s /path/to/space
.TP
daily cronjob (recommended setup):
.B 10 1 * * * /usr/sbin/ws_expirer \-c

